<!--article-->
<worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm">
    <title>Math 483 Homework 1</title>

            
	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li>
				<p>
					Review uniform vs. pointwise convergence.
				</p>
			</li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Prove that Riemann integrals are well behaved with respect to uniform convergence.
                </p>
            </li>
	  	</ul>
    </objectives>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Our main goal this semester is to prove a theorem like Theorem 3.15 in your textbook (just a little different). To do so, we need to understand uniform convergence, and why it is nice.
        </p>
    </introduction>
<page>

<definition xml:id="pointwise-convergence">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>b &gt; a</m>. We say the sequence <m>\{f_n\}_{n=0}^{\infty}</m> <term>converges pointwise</term> (written as <m>f_n\to f</m>) to <m>f</m> on <m>[a,b]</m> if for each <m>x\in [a,b]</m> and <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m>, there is some <m>N\in \mathbb{N}</m> such that if <m>n\geq N</m>, then 
            <md>
                |f_n(x) - f(x)| &lt; \epsilon.
            </md>
            
        </p>
    </statement>
</definition>

<definition xml:id="uniform-convergence">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>b &gt; a</m>. We say the sequence <m>\{f_n\}_{n=0}^{\infty}</m> <term>converges uniformy</term> (written as <m>f_n\xrightarrow[]{u}f</m>) to <m>f</m> on <m>[a,b]</m> if for each <m>\epsilon &gt; 0 </m>, there is some <m>N\in \mathbb{N}</m> such that if <m>n\geq N</m>, then 
            <md>
                |f_n(x) - f(x)| &lt; \epsilon
            </md>
            for all <m>x\in [a,b]</m>
        </p>
    </statement>
</definition>

<exercise><title>The Standard Example</title>
<statement>
    <p>
        Let <m>f_n(x) = x^n</m> and let 
        <md>f(x) =
            \begin{cases}
			0, &amp; x\in [0,1)\\
            1, &amp; x=1.
		 \end{cases}
        </md>
        Prove that <m>f_n \to f</m> pointwise on <m>[0,1]</m>, but not uniformly.
    </p>
</statement>
</exercise>

<exercise><title>Another Example</title>
<statement>
    <p>
        Let
        <md>f_n(x) =
            \begin{cases}
			n, &amp; x\in (0,1/n)\\
            0, &amp; x\in [1/n,1]\cup \{0\}.
		 \end{cases}
            
        </md>
        Prove that <m>f_n\to 0</m> on <m>[0,1]</m>, but not uniformly.
    </p>
</statement>

    
</exercise>
    
<p>
    Now we have an important theorem about uniform convergence.
</p>

<theorem xml:id="uniform-integral-limit">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>\{f_n\}_{n=0}^{\infty}</m> be a sequence of functions that are Riemann integrable on <m>[a,b]</m>. If <m>f_n\xrightarrow[]{u}f</m>, then <m>f</m> is Riemann integrable and 
            <md>
                \lim_{n\to\infty}\int_a^b f_n(x)\,dx = \int_{a}^{b} f(x)\,dx.
            </md>
            
        </p>
    </statement>
</theorem>

<exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Prove the theorem given above. Here are some hints:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Find an element of the sequence that is uniformly close to <m>f</m>. Use this to argue that <m>f</m> is bounded on <m>[a,b]</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Find a partition of <m>[a,b]</m> so that the upper sum and lower sum of the function approximating <m>f</m> are close to one another.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Argue that this implies the upper and lower sums of <m>f</m> over this partition are close to one another. This will get you integrability.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Now argue the integral of <m>f</m> is the limit of the integral of the <m>f_n</m>'s.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
            You should be making some <m>\epsilon/3</m> arguments here.
        </p>
    </statement>
</exercise>

<exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Use one of the examples above to show uniform convergence is necessary in the previous theorem.
        </p>
    </statement>
</exercise>


</page>


</worksheet>
